[Although not specified, the hantavirus involved in these cases and
those in the report below are almost certain due to Andes virus.

An image of the long-tailed pygmy rice rat (_Oligoryzomys
longicaudatus_), the sigmodontine rodent host of Andes hantavirus, can
be seen at http://www.bios.niu.edu/frayjorge/rod6.jpg.

The regions of Chile can be seen on the map at
http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Administrative_divisions_of_Chile. A
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map showing the location of Valle el
Frio, Los Lagos, can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/19Mg. -
Mod.TY]

******
[3] Chile (Aysen)
Date: Sun 21 Aug 2011
Source: Radio Santa Maria [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://www.radiosantamaria.cl/rsm/noticias/3899-virus-hanta-sexto-caso-sospechoso-en-estado-grave-en-hospital-regional.html


This Tuesday [16 Aug 2011] the head of the health unit, Claudio
Vallejos, stated that there might be a 6th case [of hantavirus
infection], the nephew of the woman who died recently of [a]
hantavirus [infection]. The suspected case is currently in serious
condition connected to mechanical ventilation in intensive care,
awaiting confirmation [of a hantavirus infection] from the Institute
of Public Health.

In addition to the 5 confirmed cases and the suspected case, there are
2 other cases of hantavirus [infection] which occurred during this
summer [2010-11]. According to projections by the Health SEREMI
[Regional Ministerial Secretariat], new patients should continue to
appear with hantavirus [infections].

Despite the cold and frosts during this winter, [conditions] have not
been sufficient to completely exterminate the rodents, and it is
foreseen that with spring commencing, the presence of mice in the
region will increase.

As for prevention, the SEREMI indicted that they now have delivered
1000 kits to families at risk, that is to say in rural and isolated
areas, expecting to deliver more preventive measures in these areas
where there is greater presence of long-tailed [rats].

